==English==
===Etymology===
[[Early Modern English]]; used at least 150 times by William Shakespeare.  Also used in [[Middle English]] by Geoffrey Chaucer, "me thinketh," and in [[Old English]] by the Alfred the Great poet, "me thincth."

In [[Middle English]] it was two words: the [[verb]] "thinketh" and the [[dative]] "me."

thinketh: it seems<br>
me: to me

===Verb===
'''methinks'''

# {{archaic}} It [[seem]]s to me.

=== Examples ===
William Shakespeare:
    methinks the truth should live from age to age,<br>
    --King Richard III: III, i 

Geoffrey Chaucer:
    Me thinketh accordant to reason<br>
    To telle you al the condicion

Alfred the Great:<br>
    Forthy me thincth betre,<br>
    gif iow swæ thincth,<BR>
    thæt we eac sumæ bec

